            . The Prosecutor deposed, that he being with his Family in the Country, his Servant came to him and told him that his Parlour Door and Bouffet were broke open and his Plate gone, whereupon he came to Town, and met one who told him where some of his Place was, and he found some of his Spoons (which he produc'd in Court) accordingly; that the rest of his Plate was carried to Dover in Order to go to France, but being stopt there, the Prisoner came back to London, and gave the Prosecutor a Particular Account of the Box of Plate so stopt, in Writing; which being inspected there, proved to be the same he had lost: that the Prisoner had been his Servant formerly, and having then behaved himself very well; had Access to his House afterwards. The Prisoner owned the <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="172101130003"></xptr> Fact. and being askt after what manner he committed it said, that he got into the House (the Door being open) about 4 a Clock in the Afternoon, and did himself under the Cellar Stairs till about 12 or 1 at Night, and then broke open the Parlour-Door, and Bouffet, and took the Goods. The Jury found him <rs id="t17210113-3-verdict17" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17210113-3-verdict17" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               Guilty
            </rs> of the Indictment. <rs id="t17210113-3-punish18" type="punishmentDescription">
